Let me look at the issue more directly. In the `UnionContext` class, I notice that the order of elements in the union depends on how they are added to the BasicNodeSet. The issue is that the `setPosition` method goes through contexts in sequence and adds nodes to the set in the order they appear in the contexts. 

Now let me check how the test is supposed to work. The problem is likely in the way the union handles document order. Looking at XPath specification, unions should maintain document order regardless of the order in which the expressions are written.

In the failing test, both `/vendor[1]/contact[1] | /vendor[1]/contact[4]` and `/vendor[1]/contact[4] | /vendor[1]/contact[1]` should return the same value because XPath unions preserve document order.

The issue might be that in `UnionContext.setPosition()`, the code creates a `BasicNodeSet` but doesn't guarantee document order. Looking at the code more carefully:

```java
while (ctx.nextSet()) {
    while (ctx.nextNode()) {
        NodePointer ptr = ctx.getCurrentNodePointer();
        if (!pointers.contains(ptr)) {
            nodeSet.add(ptr);
            pointers.add(ptr);
        }
    }
}
```

The problem is that nodes are added in the order the contexts are processed, not in document order. This causes incorrect behavior when different orders of the same union expression should yield the same document order result.

Let me analyze the `NodeSetContext` and `BasicNodeSet` classes to see if there's a method to sort by document order:

